It was a gun. >>179613800
The fertile offspring rule is a useful heuristic but it isn't exhaustive in and of itself.
Humans love to categorise things, and "species" is just what we call a somewhat distinct population, but in reality, in nature, there are broad spectra of overlapping gene pools and murky borders between what we consider separate species.

Polar bears and grizzly bears can interbreed and produce fertile offspring. They are genetically quite similar to each other, but their different phenotypes, behaviours and territorial ranges make them distinct species in their own right.

do people jump to HSR in public transportation discussions because it is all they have heard of and memorized the arguments against or because they're just a bit dim and don't understand the differences between types of services and modes?

Regional rail connects a city with regional areas (imagine that!) and Interurban rail provides fast express services to large towns and small cities there in, these might be half hourly or hourly or just a few times a day depending on demand and distances
Commuter rail provides rail to and through the suburbs of a city (regional and interurban typically keep going after the commuters last stop), it will be frequent during the morning and evening peaks but less so the rest of the time
Metro rail provides fully grade separated transit inside a city, these will maintain a high frequency all day long
And then trams/streetcars operate on the road in and around a city center and the surrounding urban area, they could be in large and medium sized cities and they could also be in regional cities too
As you can see HSR has nothing to do with a walkable city, commuter and metro trains and trams/streetcars do

Avatar: The Way Of Water has made more money in India than Endgame to become the highest-grossing foreign movie of all time in India. The inspiration for Avatar was blue-skinned Hindu gods (like Vishnu and Shiva) according to Cameron himself. Also, the word 'avatar' itself means 'divine incarnation' in the ancient Sanskrit language of India. An 'avatar' is a Hindu concept that refers to the descent of a divine being from the realm of spirit to the realm of matter where we all dwell. When Avatar 1 was released, James Cameron during one of his speeches in New Delhi mentioned "I just have loved everything, the mythology, the entire Hindu pantheon, seems so rich and vivid." He continued and said, "I didn't want to reference the Hindu religion so closely, but the subconscious association was interesting, and I hope I haven't offended anyone in doing so."
Furthermore, when Cameron was asked what exactly the word 'avatar' means, he said “It's an incarnation of one of the Hindu gods taking a flesh form. In this film what that means is that the human technology in the future is capable of injecting a human's intelligence into a remotely located body, a biological body.” (source: https://www.jagrantv.com/en-show/avatar-the-way-of-water-is-the-story-related-to-matsya-avatar-cameron-spiritual-connection-with-india-rc1037160)

Also, that liquid in Avatar: The Way Of Water which stops aging is called 'amrita' and 'amrita' is a Sanskrit word meaning 'immortality'. In Hindu mythology, amrita is the nectar of the gods and the reason why the gods are immortal/very long-lived.

"I just like blue. It’s a good color. Plus, there’s a connection to the Hindu deities, which I like conceptually." - James Cameron (source: https://nicolastang.org/2010/02/03/avatar/)

The Expanse is current era space exploration. The one thing out is the reactionless engine (Epstein drive) and the ring system which is clearly extraterrestial. Otherwise, everything is perfectly plausible. (Spacecraft needs fuel and supplies, oxygen and water is a problem, acceleration causes inertia and people on board has to brace, people living in low gravity environments are adapted to low gravity, and feel uncomfortable in normal gravity, etc.)

Avatar humans use cryo for relativistic interstellar travel, use chemical engines and chemical rockets. They need reaction mass (huge spherical containers), but the need for it is handwaved. We didn't see colonies in the solar system, but I expect a moon and a mars colony. (with scaled down isvs).

Of the two, Avatar seems to be harder sci-fi (no use of applied phlebotnium at all).
Which is bad, Avatar is the later setting, and apart from the ISVs, everything is today's tech + 5-10 years. At least directed energy weapons, or rail guns would be nice.
